/code>) is notorious for violently stripping ANSI color codes.</b> It doesn=
't matter what environment variables we set (<code data-path-to-node=3D"1" =
data-index-in-node=3D"176">FORCE_COLOR</code>); the moment PowerShell touch=
es the output stream to split it, it converts it to plain text objects and =
destroys the raw color bytes.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"2">To fix this for=
 good, <b data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"22">we need to comp=
letely ban PowerShell from touching the output.</b></p><p data-path-to-node=
=3D"3">Instead of PowerShell, we can use your portable Python executable to=
 handle the "Tee" (split) operation. I've updated the script below. It dyna=
mically creates a tiny, 9-line Python file on the fly, uses <i data-path-to=
-node=3D"3" data-index-in-node=3D"203">that</i> to run your agent and split=
 the logs, and then deletes itself. Python respects the color codes nativel=
y.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"4">Here is the code. Replace your <code data-=
path-to-node=3D"4" data-index-in-node=3D"31">.bat</code> file with this:</p=
