=3D"0">Ah, the classic "Catch-22" of logging!</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"1"=
>Here is exactly what happened:
In the <code data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"38">finally</cod=
e> block, we did the right thing and told Python, <i data-path-to-node=3D"1=
" data-index-in-node=3D"93">"Close the files so Windows will let us delete =
the temporary one."</i>
But then, inside the <code data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"18=
1">generate_html_log()</code> function, we called <code data-path-to-node=
=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"221">logger.info(...)</code>. The logger went,=
 <i data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"256">"Okay, let me write =
this message to the terminal stream!"</i> ...but we had <i data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"328">just</i> closed that stream! Hence, the =
<code data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"364">I/O operation on c=
losed file</code> crash.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"2">Since we restore <co=
de data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"17">sys.stdout =3D sys.__s=
tdout__</code> right before calling <code data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-inde=
x-in-node=3D"66">generate_html_log()</code>, the easiest and cleanest fix i=
s to just use standard <code data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"=
140">print()</code> statements inside that cleanup function instead of the =
<code data-path-to-node=3D"2" data-index-in-node=3D"203">logger</code>.</p>=
<p data-path-to-node=3D"3">Change your <code data-path-to-node=3D"3" data-i=
ndex-in-node=3D"12">generate_html_log()</code> function to look like this:<=
