CrewAI uses a UI library called <code data-path-to-node=3D"1" data-index-in=
-node=3D"67">rich</code> to draw those spinning loading animations. To anim=
ate in a terminal, it prints a line, then sends invisible <b data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"180">"Move Cursor Up"</b> and <b data-path-=
to-node=3D"1" data-index-in-node=3D"201">"Clear Line"</b> commands, and pri=
nts the next frame over the old one.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"2">Because =
our HTML converter doesn't know how to move a cursor up, it just panics and=
 prints every single frame of the animation stacked on top of each other! T=
hat is also why your newlines got swallowed=E2=80=94the raw cursor movement=
 commands fused the lines together.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"3">To fix th=
is, we have to build a tiny "Terminal Simulator" right before we convert to=
 HTML. It will literally count the "Move Up" commands and delete the previo=
us lines from our buffer, perfectly mimicking what your real terminal did.<=
