n: ease-out;"><p data-path-to-node=3D"0">Glad to hear it is finally working=
 perfectly! We definitely wrestled with some classic terminal-emulation edg=
e cases to get here.</p><p data-path-to-node=3D"1">To document the journey =
for your codebase, here is a summary of the entire debugging process we wen=
t through to build this robust logging pipeline:</p><h3 data-path-to-node=
=3D"2">1. The Architecture Rewrite (Escaping "Frankenstein" Code)</h3><ul d=
ata-path-to-node=3D"3"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0"><b data-path-to-n=
ode=3D"3,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Problem:</b> The original approa=
ch relied on writing to temporary files (<code data-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0" =
data-index-in-node=3D"73">.tmp</code>), manipulating global variables, and =
brittle <code data-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"123">finall=
y</code> blocks. This caused race conditions, file lock crashes (<code data=
-path-to-node=3D"3,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"187">WinError 32</code>), and=
 messy execution code.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"3,1,0"><b data-p=
ath-to-node=3D"3,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Solution:</b> We scrappe=
d the temp files entirely in favor of an <b data-path-to-node=3D"3,1,0" dat=
a-index-in-node=3D"65">In-Memory Buffer</b> (<code data-path-to-node=3D"3,1=
,0" data-index-in-node=3D"83">io.StringIO</code>). We wrapped the terminal =
interception logic inside a <b data-path-to-node=3D"3,1,0" data-index-in-no=
de=3D"149">Context Manager</b> (<code data-path-to-node=3D"3,1,0" data-inde=
x-in-node=3D"166">with capture_and_log:</code>). This guaranteed that stand=
ard output was seamlessly hijacked when the block started and safely restor=
ed the exact millisecond it ended, even if the agent crashed.</p></li></ul>=
<h3 data-path-to-node=3D"4">2. Fixing the Terminal-to-HTML Translation Quir=
ks</h3><ul data-path-to-node=3D"5"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0"><b da=
ta-path-to-node=3D"5,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Problem:</b> The gen=
erated HTML file contained weird characters like <code data-path-to-node=3D=
"5,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"69">[?25l</code> and the colors looked dim an=
d outdated compared to the native terminal.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-nod=
e=3D"5,1,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Fix=
:</b> * We discovered those weird characters were "cursor hide/show" comman=
ds sent by the UI library. We used regular expressions (<code data-path-to-=
node=3D"5,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"134">re.sub</code>) to surgically stri=
p them out.</p><ul data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"=
5,1,1,0,0">I initially hallucinated a <code data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1,0,0"=
 data-index-in-node=3D"27">vscode</code> color scheme which caused a <code =
data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"62">KeyError</code>. =
We quickly corrected this to use <code data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1,0,0" data=
-index-in-node=3D"105">osx</code> (or <code data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1,0,0"=
 data-index-in-node=3D"113">tango</code>), which are officially supported b=
y <code data-path-to-node=3D"5,1,1,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"155">ansi2htm=
l</code> and successfully restored the bright, modern terminal colors.</p><=
/li></ul></li></ul><h3 data-path-to-node=3D"6">3. The "Final Boss": Animati=
on Stacking</h3><ul data-path-to-node=3D"7"><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,0=
,0"><b data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Problem:</b=
> The terminal uses hidden "Move Cursor Up" and "Clear Line" commands to cr=
eate spinning loading animations (like CrewAI's <code data-path-to-node=3D"=
7,0,0" data-index-in-node=3D"134">rich</code> spinners). The HTML converter=
 didn't understand how to move a cursor <i data-path-to-node=3D"7,0,0" data=
-index-in-node=3D"208">backwards</i>, so it just printed every single frame=
 of the animation stacked on top of each other, flooding the HTML file with=
 duplicate lines.</p></li><li><p data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0"><b data-path-t=
o-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"0">The Solution:</b> We built a <b d=
ata-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"25">Mini Terminal Simulato=
r</b> right before the HTML conversion step. We wrote logic to parse the ra=
w text, track carriage returns (<code data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-inde=
x-in-node=3D"150">\r</code>), actively count the "Cursor Up" commands (<cod=
e data-path-to-node=3D"7,1,0" data-index-in-node=3D"196">\x1B[1A</code>), a=
nd programmatically delete the previous lines from our memory buffer.</p></=
li></ul><p data-path-to-node=3D"8"><b data-path-to-node=3D"8" data-index-in=
-node=3D"0">The Result:</b> You now have a production-grade logger that out=
puts a pristine text file, beautifully styled HTML, and runs entirely in RA=
M without risking system crashes. Great job sticking with it through the ed=
ge cases!</p></div></message-content><!----></div></structured-content-cont=
